	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">If we're not using some standard gamma when discussing palettes then we're not even discussing the same color variations.</div>
<br />
<br />The NES palette issue is so complex. You have the NES video waveform itself, then the decoder in the TV, the picture tube's non-linear response, and the colors of the phosphors it uses. That gives variation in how a NES looks. Then on an emulator you have variation in which NES palette you use, any color correction done by the OS/video card, the video card's D/A curves, whatever the monitor's circuitry does to the signal, the picture tube's non-linear response, and the colors of its phosphors.
<br />
<br />In theory, for an emulator we can calibrate everything so that a given palette looks the same on everyone's computer, leaving the only remaining problem the choice of palette. But is this calibration a real possibility?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


